A welcome addition to the neighborhood! The good:  high-quality, made to order burgers where you can build your own burger choosing from several meat options - my fav is Bison! - buns or greens, toppings.  Organic, grass-fed meat definitely worth the extra buck or two. The bad:  service is at best confused.  Waitstaff seems positive but a bit clueless.    They are not so familiar with the menu, they never heard of bringing the salads, apps before the main course, and I have had them come back to check on what was ordered multiple times.  Since the staff seems eager and positive, I suspect poor management is the issue.  The layout of the restaurant is longer and narrow resulting in a noisy experience with the music a bit too loud.  Also, my clothes smell like the burger joint afterwards - they need better venting.

Being celiac, Bareburger has been a staple restaurant for me for over 2 years. It’s so disappointing that over that time the chain has gone down in quality. Many times the fries come over fried, too soft, or cold, or the burgers come undercooked. Tonight was no different. Firstly, they lost my order & “had to find it”. I had the buffalo chicken sandwich, waffle fries and coconut ice cream strawberry milkshake. Secondly, the chicken was burnt and the fries were cold. Finally, my fiancé had a regular burger and fries. His burger was undercooked, although he made sure to ask for well done, and he never got the fries. I think this will be the last time we eat at Bareburger...unless there are no other choices.

No flavor, no real crunch, just super bland. The vegan burgers were alright. I feel like the vegan burgers I had from the Bareburger Court St Brooklyn location tasted juicier and weren’t “just slapped together”. The milkshakes were the best part of our dinner here. Especially my husband’s vegan mint chocolate cookies & cream shake was really delicious! Our waitress Hannah W was kind and helpful. However, I’m sad to say that my expectations for our UWS Bareburger dinner weren’t met. I left with a full, but unsatisfied disappointed stomach. Maybe the time of our visit 5:00pm on a Saturday had something to do with it, because it was pretty packed when we arrived. I don’t like writing this kinda sad review, but I have to keep it real.

🌱🍔This place has an extensive menu of customizable burgers with tons of vegan options. You can choose between the Beyond Meat patty, the Impossible patty, or their house-made veggie burger patties. They have all their vegan ingredients clearly listed. The normal bun is not vegan friendly, but they have some whole grain bun that is, as well as collard greens available to wrap the burger in. They have vegan cheese and vegan sauces as well, including vegan mayo. The french fries are fried in vegetable oil and are listed as vegan friendly on the menu. Best of all, they have vegan shakes! Bareburger has an extremely compelling menu, and I love burgers, so it was a sure thing that I'd hit up this Greenwich village spot. They have elk, bison, and ostrich burgers on the menu. And anyone who's read my blog knows how much I love a good ostrich steak.  Unfortunately I was a touch disappointed by Bareburger. The atmosphere is a little weird - it's very bright and is a big open cafeteria like space. I actually don't mind that it was big, but it didn't feel very intimate. I guess this is more of a personal preference and something I've come to expect from other burger joints in NYC, but I guess I also am a little uncomfortable scarfing down an entire burger in harsh light. It's a guilty pleasure so I'd like to think I'm hiding it at least a little bit.  But, down to the brass tax - how was the burger? It was... okay. I ordered the classic - just wanted to taste the meat with a touch of toppings. I got it with bison meat, and asked for it medium well. I like a burger with a touch of pink, but like for almost all of the meat to have been a little cooked. The medium well bison burger came completely well done. And, it wasn't that flavorful. I've made bison burgers at home and the difference between bison meat and regular beef is profound. Not here, unfortunately. The bun was a brioche bun and was quite good. The toppings were adequate. The caramelized onions weren't so much caramelized as slightly sautéed...  But, it was tasty.  The fries as well were okay but not great. They were a touch soggy, and not super flavorful. The most damning thing, in my opinion, was the lack of heinz ketchup, or an equally good tasting substitute. They utilize muir gardens brand, which is (generously speaking) watery and unflavorful. I realize that their focus is on being all organic and if you're going to go through the trouble of having walls made of cork you're going to make sure you utilize organic ketchup. I get that. But heinz makes organic ketchup too, and it doesn't taste terrible. So... that's just a suggestion.  Overall I really wanted to like this place. I really wanted to be able to find an awesome affordable burger joint with a wide range of beef that was just tremendous. Bareburger didn't quite meet the expectations. But, I may go back to try the elk burger.
